Exploratory Analysis

Project title

How Income Levels are Affected by Race, Gender, and Education

Authors

Brianna, Aldrich, Audrey and Rahma

Date

May 17, 2024

Abstract

Our main question is: to what extent do disparities between racial groups in education and occupation affect income? This question is important because we want to understand how the intersection of certain factors affect economic inequality in the United States. We plan to analyze data sets in order to recognize patterns and trends in how identity factors such as race and gender influence eventual economic outcomes.

Keywords

Income, race, gender, education

Introduction

Our project primarily investigates the data trends of income grouped by race. We will also be analyzing other considered factors such as gender, age, occupation, and education level. Our aim is to understand how these factors affect economic outcomes in households in the United States. Some research questions that motivate our research topic are: to what extent do disparities between racial groups in education and occupation affect household income? What are the primary factors that seem to influence household income? How does the intersection of race, gender, and education level affect household income? We want to understand which of these factors may weigh more in terms of salary outcomes, and how these factors may help or hurt certain groups of people. This is an important concept to analyze in order to understand how certain privileged groups are able to stay privileged, and how difficult it can be for marginalized groups to break the cycle of poverty. Additionally, this is an important research topic as we can address systemic inequalities and find ways to develop attainable solutions. This can provide both systemic and historical contexts into how racialized institutions are still affecting our society today. We will be able to better understand how intersectionality and overlapping factors influence economic outcomes.

Related Work

While our topic primarily focuses on income inequality as a result of racial disparities, there are many contributing factors to this inequality. Intersectionality is the idea that multiple forms of inequality or disadvantages sometimes compound themselves and create obstacles that often are not understood among conventional ways of thinking. Understanding that racial disparities are not the lone contributing factor to income inequality broadens the debate to consider other factors such as gender, education, sexuality, and other defining characteristics of unique individuals that can contribute to income inequality. The following three articles reaffirm the role race plays regarding income, as well as highlighting other contributing factors and providing possible solutions to combat it. The first article by the U.S. Department of Treasury highlights racial inequality in the United States. They define racial inequality as the unequal distribution of resources, power and economic opportunity across race in a society. The article includes various statistics and graphs that depict the prevalence of the issue. For example, a graph showed that the median household income in 2020 was roughly $46,000 and $55,000 for Black and Hispanic workers, respectively, compared to $75,000 and $95,000 for white and Asian households. Racial Inequality in the United States. U.S. Department of the Treasury, 21 July 2022, home.treasury.gov/news/featured-stories/racial-inequality-in-the-united-states#:~:text=In%20addition%2C%20Black%20and%20Hispanic,as%20shown%20in%20Figure%204. The next article by the Pew Research Center reaffirms the inequality in income between races, but it adds another layer of complexity to the issue. Along with racial disparities, they also consider how other factors, such as gender, play a role in income inequality. They make this abundantly clear with the following statistics: In 2022, Black women earned 70% as much as White men and Hispanic women earned only 65% as much. The ratio for White women stood at 83% about the same as the earnings gap overall, while Asian women were closer to parity with White men, making 93% as much. Kochhar, Rakesh. The Enduring Grip of the Gender Pay Gap. Pew Research Center, Pew Research Center, 1 Mar.2023, www.pewresearch.org/social-trends/2023/03/01/the-enduring-grip-of-the-gender-pay-gap/#:~:text=In%202022%2C%20Black%20women%20earned,%2C%20making%2093%25%20as%20much. Lastly, another article by the Pew Research Center analyzes where the power lies when it comes to fighting income inequality. According to their research, most Americans agree that the federal government and large corporations hold high responsibility in reducing inequality. They included a graph that ranks the responsibility/power for a certain group to reduce inequality. The results are as follows: The federal government at 66%, large business and corporations at 62%, state governments at 52%, wealthy individuals at 46%, and lastly churches/other religious organizations at 13%. This shows that the solution to income inequality lies among those with positions of high power. Juliana Menasce Horowitz, Ruth Igielnik and Rakesh Kochhar. 4. Views on Reducing Economic Inequality. Pew Research Center, Pew Research Center, 9 Jan.2020, www.pewresearch.org/social-trends/2020/01/09/views-on-reducing-economic-inequality/.

(at least 200 words) The Income Dataset from Kaggle, despite its usefulness for economic and demographic analysis, presents several challenges that could undermine its effectiveness and ethical integrity. The dataset lacks comprehensive documentation detailing the methodology of data collection, which raises questions about the accuracy and representativeness of the data. This gap in information makes it difficult to assess the reliability of any findings derived from the data. Also, theres concern about the completeness of the dataset. Missing values or incomplete records can skew analyses, leading to potentially biased outcomes that do not accurately reflect the population being studied. The dataset may harbor inherent biases if the data collection did not adequately control for a diverse and representative sample. Such biases can affect the generalizability of the results, potentially leading to conclusions that are not applicable to broader populations. Another significant issue is the timeliness of the data. If the data was collected in the past, it might not reflect current economic realities or demographic shifts, which can be crucial for studies intended to inform current policy or business decisions. Lastly, the use of personal income data involves several ethical and legal considerations, particularly concerning privacy and consent. If the data includes personally identifiable information or was collected without explicit consent, there could be serious ethical violations, alongside potential legal repercussions.

Summary Information

The dataset includes a total of 38,097 records. The most common race is White. There are 293 females and 606 males. The average age of individuals is approximately 38.5 years. The most common job for men is in craft repair, while the most common job for women is in administration or clerical work. These findings provide a comprehensive overview of the key demographic and job-related information in the dataset.

Table

Table of aggregate information

# Load necessary libraries
library(dplyr)

# Load the dataset
data <- read.csv("./income_data.csv")

aggregate_table <- data %>%
  group_by(education) %>%
  summarise(
    `Total Count` = n(),
    `Average Age` = round(mean(age, na.rm = TRUE), 1),
    `Black Count` = sum(race == "Black", na.rm = TRUE),
    `White Count` = sum(race == "White", na.rm = TRUE),
    `Male Count` = sum(gender == "Male", na.rm = TRUE),
    `Female Count` = sum(gender == "Female", na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(`Total Count`))

# Print the aggregate table
print(aggregate_table)

library(tidyverse)
library(readr)

data <- read_csv("./income_data.csv")
ggplot(data, aes(x = race, fill = workclass)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  labs(x = "Race", y = "Count", fill = "Work Class", title = "Comparing Race and    Work Class")

This chart displays race compared to workclass. As shown, White individuals have the highest rate of employment in all of the included classes (federal gov, local gov, private, self-emp-inc, self-emp-not-inc, and state-gov). The most noticeable disparity is the difference between White people that are employed in private work classes compared to those of other races. White has the highest number, with a count over 500, whereas Black comes in second, with less than 100. This not only shows that race plays a role in employment, but that its impact seems to be significant. Level of employment directly translates to level of income, which is why analyzing how race plays a role in employment is important to tackling racial disparities regarding income.

Chart 3

summary_data <- data %>%
  group_by(gender, education) %>%
  summarise(Count = n()) %>%
  ungroup()

ggplot(summary_data, aes(x = education, y = Count, fill = gender)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Comparison of Gender and Education",
       x = "Education Level",
       y = "Count",
       fill = "Gender")

I chose this chart to display the gender differences in education level because it can help us understand how gender roles play a part in completion of education. We can see through the bar chart that most of the bars for males are higher than females in terms of education level. This could be attributed to the fact that more entries in the dataset were male instead of female, but it could also indicate that males completed higher levels of education in general.
